<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,500,1607]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,716,742]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Description.</emphasis>
Based on the best-preserved specimen (ECOSUR-3070): complete with 24 segments. TL= 1.7 mm, TW= 0.6 mm. Body short, broad, tapered posteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[843,936,752,779]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[170,1405,181,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-26@8.[170,1417,181,1882]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Paleanotus bellis (Johnson, 1897), non-type specimen (ECOSUR-3070). A) Complete fragmented body. B) Drawing of prostomium, dorsal view. C) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. D) Oocyte. E) Parapodium from segment 15. F) Lateral palea. G) Subunit 1. H) Main palea. I) Median paleae. J) Unit 1. K) Unit 2. L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. Scales: 10 µm (JKLM), 20 µm (D), 50 µm (BCFGHI), 100 µm (E), 500 µm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702019/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3A</figureCitation>
). Body pale yellow. Paleae fan translucent, slightly imbricated dorsally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,500,1607]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Prostomium visible among the first four segments. Lateral antennae short, inserted on antero-ventral prostomial margin, median antenna slightly shorter than lateral ones, inserted in front of the anterior eyes. Eyes red-violet, two pairs. Nuchal organ small, oblong, partially covering the prostomium (
<figureCitation box="[940,1028,896,923]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[170,1405,181,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-26@8.[170,1417,181,1882]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Paleanotus bellis (Johnson, 1897), non-type specimen (ECOSUR-3070). A) Complete fragmented body. B) Drawing of prostomium, dorsal view. C) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. D) Oocyte. E) Parapodium from segment 15. F) Lateral palea. G) Subunit 1. H) Main palea. I) Median paleae. J) Unit 1. K) Unit 2. L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. Scales: 10 µm (JKLM), 20 µm (D), 50 µm (BCFGHI), 100 µm (E), 500 µm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702019/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3B</figureCitation>
). Palps short, oval, visible in ventral view. Mouth fold wide, placed between segment 3 and 4. Pharynx muscular eversible, not exposed, stylets slender.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,500,1607]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Parapodium from segment 15, notochaetae in three main groups (
<figureCitation box="[935,1023,968,995]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[170,1405,181,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-26@8.[170,1417,181,1882]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Paleanotus bellis (Johnson, 1897), non-type specimen (ECOSUR-3070). A) Complete fragmented body. B) Drawing of prostomium, dorsal view. C) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. D) Oocyte. E) Parapodium from segment 15. F) Lateral palea. G) Subunit 1. H) Main palea. I) Median paleae. J) Unit 1. K) Unit 2. L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. Scales: 10 µm (JKLM), 20 µm (D), 50 µm (BCFGHI), 100 µm (E), 500 µm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702019/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3E</figureCitation>
). Notochaetae: lateral group inserted below notaciculum, 1–2 paleae, slender and symmetrical, with 6–7 internal ribs (
<figureCitation box="[1062,1147,1004,1031]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[170,1405,181,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-26@8.[170,1417,181,1882]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Paleanotus bellis (Johnson, 1897), non-type specimen (ECOSUR-3070). A) Complete fragmented body. B) Drawing of prostomium, dorsal view. C) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. D) Oocyte. E) Parapodium from segment 15. F) Lateral palea. G) Subunit 1. H) Main palea. I) Median paleae. J) Unit 1. K) Unit 2. L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. Scales: 10 µm (JKLM), 20 µm (D), 50 µm (BCFGHI), 100 µm (E), 500 µm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702019/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3F</figureCitation>
); subunit 1, 1 palea, slender, shorter and symmetrical, with 7 internal ribs (
<figureCitation box="[705,794,1040,1067]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[170,1405,181,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-26@8.[170,1417,181,1882]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Paleanotus bellis (Johnson, 1897), non-type specimen (ECOSUR-3070). A) Complete fragmented body. B) Drawing of prostomium, dorsal view. C) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. D) Oocyte. E) Parapodium from segment 15. F) Lateral palea. G) Subunit 1. H) Main palea. I) Median paleae. J) Unit 1. K) Unit 2. L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. Scales: 10 µm (JKLM), 20 µm (D), 50 µm (BCFGHI), 100 µm (E), 500 µm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702019/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3G</figureCitation>
). Main group, 9–11 paleae, broad, curved and asymmetrical, with (17) 18–19 (21) internal ribs and 3 finely raised ribs (
<figureCitation box="[853,943,1076,1103]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[170,1405,181,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-26@8.[170,1417,181,1882]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Paleanotus bellis (Johnson, 1897), non-type specimen (ECOSUR-3070). A) Complete fragmented body. B) Drawing of prostomium, dorsal view. C) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. D) Oocyte. E) Parapodium from segment 15. F) Lateral palea. G) Subunit 1. H) Main palea. I) Median paleae. J) Unit 1. K) Unit 2. L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. Scales: 10 µm (JKLM), 20 µm (D), 50 µm (BCFGHI), 100 µm (E), 500 µm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702019/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3H</figureCitation>
). Median group, 3–4 paleae, shorter, curved and asymmetrical, with 10–12 internal ribs and 3–4 raised ribs (
<figureCitation box="[883,963,1112,1139]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[170,1405,181,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-26@8.[170,1417,181,1882]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Paleanotus bellis (Johnson, 1897), non-type specimen (ECOSUR-3070). A) Complete fragmented body. B) Drawing of prostomium, dorsal view. C) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. D) Oocyte. E) Parapodium from segment 15. F) Lateral palea. G) Subunit 1. H) Main palea. I) Median paleae. J) Unit 1. K) Unit 2. L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. Scales: 10 µm (JKLM), 20 µm (D), 50 µm (BCFGHI), 100 µm (E), 500 µm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702019/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3I</figureCitation>
). All paleae groups are covered with fine denticles over each internal rib.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,500,1607]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
Neuropodium conical, larger than notopodium. Neurochaetae: unit 1, 1–3 superior spinigers, blades straight and long, 4–5 times longer than wide (
<figureCitation box="[537,617,1220,1247]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[170,1405,181,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-26@8.[170,1417,181,1882]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Paleanotus bellis (Johnson, 1897), non-type specimen (ECOSUR-3070). A) Complete fragmented body. B) Drawing of prostomium, dorsal view. C) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. D) Oocyte. E) Parapodium from segment 15. F) Lateral palea. G) Subunit 1. H) Main palea. I) Median paleae. J) Unit 1. K) Unit 2. L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. Scales: 10 µm (JKLM), 20 µm (D), 50 µm (BCFGHI), 100 µm (E), 500 µm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702019/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3J</figureCitation>
). Unit 2, 4–5 falcigers, blades straight and medium-sized, 3 times longer than wide (
<figureCitation box="[278,369,1256,1283]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[170,1405,181,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-26@8.[170,1417,181,1882]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Paleanotus bellis (Johnson, 1897), non-type specimen (ECOSUR-3070). A) Complete fragmented body. B) Drawing of prostomium, dorsal view. C) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. D) Oocyte. E) Parapodium from segment 15. F) Lateral palea. G) Subunit 1. H) Main palea. I) Median paleae. J) Unit 1. K) Unit 2. L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. Scales: 10 µm (JKLM), 20 µm (D), 50 µm (BCFGHI), 100 µm (E), 500 µm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702019/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3K</figureCitation>
). Unit 3, 5–6 falcigers, blades straight and short, 2 times longer than wide (
<figureCitation box="[1227,1315,1256,1283]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[170,1405,181,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-26@8.[170,1417,181,1882]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Paleanotus bellis (Johnson, 1897), non-type specimen (ECOSUR-3070). A) Complete fragmented body. B) Drawing of prostomium, dorsal view. C) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. D) Oocyte. E) Parapodium from segment 15. F) Lateral palea. G) Subunit 1. H) Main palea. I) Median paleae. J) Unit 1. K) Unit 2. L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. Scales: 10 µm (JKLM), 20 µm (D), 50 µm (BCFGHI), 100 µm (E), 500 µm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702019/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3L</figureCitation>
). Unit 4, 4 falcigers, blades straight and short, 2 times longer than wide (
<figureCitation box="[834,928,1292,1319]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[170,1405,181,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-26@8.[170,1417,181,1882]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Paleanotus bellis (Johnson, 1897), non-type specimen (ECOSUR-3070). A) Complete fragmented body. B) Drawing of prostomium, dorsal view. C) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. D) Oocyte. E) Parapodium from segment 15. F) Lateral palea. G) Subunit 1. H) Main palea. I) Median paleae. J) Unit 1. K) Unit 2. L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. Scales: 10 µm (JKLM), 20 µm (D), 50 µm (BCFGHI), 100 µm (E), 500 µm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702019/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3M</figureCitation>
). Pygidium quadrate, with two anal cirri (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[170,1405,181,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-26@8.[170,1417,181,1882]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Paleanotus bellis (Johnson, 1897), non-type specimen (ECOSUR-3070). A) Complete fragmented body. B) Drawing of prostomium, dorsal view. C) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. D) Oocyte. E) Parapodium from segment 15. F) Lateral palea. G) Subunit 1. H) Main palea. I) Median paleae. J) Unit 1. K) Unit 2. L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. Scales: 10 µm (JKLM), 20 µm (D), 50 µm (BCFGHI), 100 µm (E), 500 µm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702019/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3C</figureCitation>
). Oocyte size: 47.9–59.5 µm (n=3) (
<figureCitation box="[595,685,1328,1355]" captionStart="FIGURE 3" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1906,1930]" captionTargetBox="[170,1405,181,1880]" captionTargetId="figure-26@8.[170,1417,181,1882]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 3. Paleanotus bellis (Johnson, 1897), non-type specimen (ECOSUR-3070). A) Complete fragmented body. B) Drawing of prostomium, dorsal view. C) Drawing of pygidium, ventral view. D) Oocyte. E) Parapodium from segment 15. F) Lateral palea. G) Subunit 1. H) Main palea. I) Median paleae. J) Unit 1. K) Unit 2. L) Unit 3. M) Unit 4. Scales: 10 µm (JKLM), 20 µm (D), 50 µm (BCFGHI), 100 µm (E), 500 µm (A)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702019" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702019/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 3D</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,500,1607]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,298,1364,1390]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Habitat.</emphasis>
Intertidal to subtidal (0.5– 
<quantity box="[596,641,1364,1391]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" unit="m" value="8.0">8 m</quantity>
). Specimens of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Johnson" baseAuthorityYear="1897" box="[816,904,1364,1390]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Paleanotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="bellis">
<emphasis box="[816,904,1364,1390]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">P. bellis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were collected on sand, rocks, pier piles, and as epibionts of fouling community. Specimens of this species have been previously recorded on seaweed and among tunicates attached to pier piles (
<bibRefCitation author="Johnson, H. P." box="[505,665,1436,1463]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="153 - 198" refId="ref37057" refString="Johnson, H. P. (1897) A preliminary account of the marine annelids of the Pacific coast, with descriptions of new species, Part I: The Euphrosynidae, Amphinomidae, Palmyridae, Polynoidae, and Sigalionidae. Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, Zoology, Series 3, 1, 153 - 198." type="journal article" year="1897">Johnson 1897</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,1118,1472,1499]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,500,1607]" box="[199,1118,1472,1499]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,1472,1498]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Distribution.</emphasis>
From Monterey, 
<collectingRegion box="[548,662,1472,1498]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">California</collectingRegion>
to 
<collectingRegion box="[697,777,1473,1499]" country="Honduras" name="La Paz" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">La Paz</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[788,1006,1472,1499]" country="Mexico" name="Baja California Sur" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Baja California Sur</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[1022,1105,1472,1499]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1171,1195]" captionTargetBox="[171,1417,186,1141]" captionTargetId="figure-15@25.[165,1422,181,1147]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 12. Previous and new records of chrysopetalids in the Tropical Eastern Pacific. Empty symbols indicate historic records." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5702057" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5702057/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 12</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,500,1607]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1509,1535]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Remarks.</emphasis>
Examined specimens agree with the original description of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Johnson" baseAuthorityYear="1897" box="[984,1072,1508,1534]" class="Polychaeta" family="Chrysopetalidae" genus="Paleanotus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Phyllodocida" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="bellis">
<emphasis box="[984,1072,1508,1534]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">P. bellis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Johnson, H. P." box="[1113,1289,1508,1535]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="153 - 198" refId="ref37057" refString="Johnson, H. P. (1897) A preliminary account of the marine annelids of the Pacific coast, with descriptions of new species, Part I: The Euphrosynidae, Amphinomidae, Palmyridae, Polynoidae, and Sigalionidae. Proceedings of the California Academy of Sciences, Zoology, Series 3, 1, 153 - 198." type="journal article" year="1897">Johnson (1897)</bibRefCitation>
. This species was previously recorded from the southern Mexican Pacific (
<bibRefCitation author="Cruz-Gomez, C. &amp; Bastida-Zavala, J. R." box="[843,1265,1544,1571]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="61 - 88" refId="ref35545" refString="Cruz-Gomez, C. &amp; Bastida-Zavala, J. R. (2018) Chrysopetalids (Phyllodocida: Chrysopetalidae) from the southern Mexican Pacific, including a new species. Zootaxa, 4521 (1), 61 - 88. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4521.1.3" type="journal article" year="2018">Cruz-Gómez &amp; Bastida-Zavala 2018</bibRefCitation>
); however, this record was mistaken and is now emended through the recognition of a new species described below.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
